      {this.state.howItWorks &&
      <div className="container">
      <br/>
      <h4>DecentPay Payment Contracts</h4>
      <p>This utility allows for two parties to enter into a transparent multi-payment agreement using either ETH or DAI. There are no constraints on the contract's value or number of payments. Each agreement is an
      individually deployed smart contract on the Ethereum blockchain and fully controlled and managed by the two parties involved. </p>
      <p>The parameters of the contract are set when the contract is initiated  as one would set rules in a traditional written contract between two parties. The main difference is that DecentPay contracts are controlled by code, and
      cannot be manipulated once deployed.</p>
      <p>When work is promised in exchange for payment between two parties, especially those that do not know each other, a decentralized payment contract can ease concerns and build trust. The person doing the work, the <i>payee</i>,
      can see that the <i>payer</i> not only posseses the funds to complete the entire contract, but is willing to lock the funds into the contract as a good faith measure. The hope is to eliminate uncertainty,
      delays, and fees involved in traditional payment systems.</p>
      <br/>
      <h6>Moving away from "The check is in the mail".</h6>
      <br/>
      <p>Additional dissolution mechanics built into the contracts provide a way out for the parties in case things are not going as planned. They allow the <i>payer</i> to recover funds while giving the <i>payee</i>an opportunity to
      be paid for completed work with a worst case scenario situation where the next payment is split between the two.</p>
      <br/>
      <div className="border border-secondary shadow" style={{padding: 9, backgroundColor:'WhiteSmoke'}}>
      <h5>Process:</h5>

      <p>First, <i>payer</i> and <i>payee</i> must agree to some basic contract parameters: total value of the contract, total number of (equal) payments, and a delay, in days, that will be implemented before a party can force dissolve the contract (more on this below).</p>
      <p>Next, the contract is deployed. Anyone can deploy the contract as long as they know the contract paramters and the Ethereum addresses of the <i>payer</i> and <i>payee</i>. Note that the person deploying the contract inherits no control over the
      contract unless the contract is deployed by the <i>payer</i> or the <i>payee</i>. </p>
      <p>Once the payment contract is deployed, the paying party must first pre-deposit the full value of promised work into the contract. </p>
      <p>Finally, when a contract is funded and active, both parties can sequentially request and approve payments as working progress is made. This will continue for the total number of payments until the remaining balance of the contract is depleted and the <i>payee</i>
      receives the funds. </p>
      <h6>All contract functions are available through the contract dashboard which will be presented once the contract is deployed.</h6>
      </div>
      <br/>
      <br/>
      <div className="border border-secondary shadow" style={{padding: 9, backgroundColor:'WhiteSmoke'}}>
      <h5>Protections:</h5>
      <br/>
      <p> DecentPay decentralized contracts protect both the <i>payer</i> and the <i>payee</i>.</p>
      <div className="container">
      <ul className="list-group">

      <li className="alert alert-secondary list-group-item" role="alert">The <i>payer</i> is able to release payments in multiple draws based on milestone completion on the part of the <i>payee</i>.</li>
      <li className="alert alert-secondary list-group-item" role="alert">The payee is able to validate availability of the funds, and knows that as soon as work is completed and approved the payment will
      be completed without unecessary fuss.</li>


      <li>In case a contract goes south, there are various options for payer and payee to dissolve the contract based on rules implemented into the platform that help
      protect both the payer and the payee.
      <ul>
      <li>If both parties are unhappy with the contract and want to withdraw they can "move to dissolve" the contract. The contract can then be immediately dissolved. </li>
      <ul>
      <li>If the next payment has not yet been requested by the payee, the payer receives the full remaining value of the contract. </li>
      <li>If the payee has already requested the next payment and both parties agree to dissolve, the payee receives the next payment and then the payer is sent the remaining funds held in the contract.</li>
      <li>Payee is restricted from requesting the next payment after moving to dissolve the contract.</li>
      <li>Payee cannot move to dissolve a contract after requesting the next payment unless payer has moved to dissolve first.</li>
      </ul>
      <li>If only one party wants to dissolve the contract they have three options:</li>
      <ul>
      <li>Convince other party to accept dissolution of the contract by "moving to dissolve" per above.</li>
      <li>Force dissolution of the contract by initiating a "cool down" timer (set during contract deployment) which once expired allows either party to immediately force the dissolution of the contract.</li>
      <ul>
      <li>Contract can continue with progress payments during this period.</li>
      <li>The timer encourages both parties to come to an agreement and continue the contract, while preventing the payee from locking the payer's funds up indefinitely.</li>
      <li>The timer is set by number of days. The "dissolve menu" on the contract dashboard will indicate when the timer will expire. At that point a button will appear allowing the contract to be forcefully dissolved.</li>
      <li>Any contract forcefully dissolved will split the next payment between the payer and the payee, and send remaining funds back to the payer.</li>
      </ul>
      <li>Force dissolution of the contract by sending all funds to a mediator address.</li>
      <ul>
      <li>Both payer and payee must set a mediator address and both mediator addresses much match.</li>
      <li>Mediator can be a third party that is willing to help payer and payee come to an agreement and distribute the funds off contract.</li>
      <li>Upon successfully dissolving the contract in this manner the mediator is sent all remaining contract funds immediately and the original payment contract is terminated.</li>
      </ul>
      </ul>
      </ul>
      </li>
      </ul>
      </div>
      </div>

      <br/>
      <h4>***Each payment contract is an independent smart contract on the Ethereum blockchain.***</h4>
      <h4>***DecentPay has no control or jurisdiction over the smart contract once deployed.***</h4>
